Latino voters and new shifts in
the race for president.

00:28.295 --> 00:32.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Plus: A mysterious
infection causes an olive crisis
in Italy.

00:32.966 --> 00:35.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIOVANNI MELCARNE, Oliver Grower
(through translator): What is
certain is that these

00:35.302 --> 00:38.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plants are dying, that these
plants are drying, and we don't
know what the future will be,

00:38.839 --> 00:40.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and we don't even know that
there's a solution to this
situation.

00:40.941 --> 00:47.948 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:47.948 --> 00:52.452 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

00:52.452 --> 01:02.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Obama
today insisted coalition forces
are hitting back at Islamic

01:02.462 --> 01:08.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
State militants harder than
ever. As a result, he said, the
group also known as ISIL has

01:08.402 --> 01:14.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lost key leaders and control of
large swathes of Iraqi and
Syrian territories. The
president

01:14.808 --> 01:19.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
outlined the progress after
meeting at the Pentagon with his
national security advisers.

01:19.313 --> 01:23.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: Every day, we
destroy as well more of ISIL's

01:23.951 --> 01:28.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
forces, their fighting
positions, bunkers, and staging
areas, their heavy weapons,
bomb-making

01:28.322 --> 01:31.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
factories, compounds
and training camps.

01:31.391 --> 01:36.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In many places, ISIL has lost
its freedom of maneuver, because
they know, if they mass

01:36.096 --> 01:39.099 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
their forces, we
will wipe them out.

01:39.099 --> 01:42.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The president
also called on allies in the
Middle East to step up their

01:42.336 --> 01:45.605 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
contributions to the fight.

01:45.605 --> 01:52.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Late today, Saudi Arabia
announced that it is forming a
34-state Islamic military
coalition

01:52.212 --> 01:56.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to combat terrorism. It includes
Arab countries like Egypt and
Qatar and Islamic countries

01:56.616 --> 01:59.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
like Turkey and Pakistan.

01:59.720 --> 02:05.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Investigators in
Egypt say October's crash of a
Russian passenger jet can't be

02:05.425 --> 02:11.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
called terrorism yet. That's in
direct conflict with Russian,
American and British statements

02:11.465 --> 02:16.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that a bomb was probably to
blame. A group linked to the
Islamic State had claimed
responsibility

02:16.503 --> 02:22.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for the Sinai crash that killed
all 224 people on board. Egypt's
assessment is a preliminary

02:22.642 --> 02:25.946 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
finding. Their
investigation is ongoing.

02:25.946 --> 02:32.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In Argentina, at
least 43 police officers died
today when their bus careened

02:32.386 --> 02:39.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
off a bridge, plunging 65 feet
into a ravine. The crash
occurred near Salta, roughly
1,000

02:39.659 --> 02:45.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
miles north of Buenos Aires.
Rescue crews pulled victims from
the overturned bus, which

02:45.232 --> 02:48.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was carrying around 60 people.
Investigators believe the
accident was caused by a
ruptured

02:48.869 --> 02:50.937 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
tire.

02:50.937 --> 02:57.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Up to 750,000 people
have evacuated the Central
Philippines as a powerful
typhoon

02:57.711 --> 03:04.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
made landfall. The storm slammed
into a tiny village on the
northern tip of Samar Island

03:04.217 --> 03:10.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
today, packing wind gusts up to
115 miles per hour. Authorities
warned the heavy rain

03:10.157 --> 03:15.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
could trigger storm surges,
landslides, and coastal flooding
of up to 13 feet. There were

03:15.195 --> 03:19.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
no -- there was no immediate
word of casualties.

03:19.366 --> 03:24.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Official results
out today showed France's
Conservative Party held off

03:24.438 --> 03:29.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a challenge by the far-right
National Front in the second
round of regional elections.

03:29.843 --> 03:35.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Conservatives, led by former
President Nicolas Sarkozy,
captured 40 percent of Sunday's

03:35.582 --> 03:40.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
votes. Current President
Francois Hollande's Socialist
Party won nearly 29 percent, and

03:40.654 --> 03:44.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the National Front
took 27 percent.

03:44.891 --> 03:48.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sarkozy warned the far-right's
strong showing in the first
round of votes should have
everyone

03:48.995 --> 03:51.698 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on guard.

03:51.698 --> 03:55.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANCOIS HOLLANDE, French
President (through translator):
This mobilization for our
candidates

03:55.335 --> 04:00.140 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the second round should under
no circumstances allow us to
forget the warnings which were

04:00.140 --> 04:05.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sent to all political leaders,
us included, during the first
round of those regional
elections.

04:05.145 --> 04:10.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: While the
National front garnered its
largest number of votes in any
election,

04:10.117 --> 04:14.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it still failed to win a single
region in the polls. Last night,
its leader, Marine

04:14.254 --> 04:17.157 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Le Pen, downplayed the loss.

04:17.157 --> 04:19.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARINE LE PEN, President,
National Front Party (through
translator): The National Front
will

04:19.593 --> 04:27.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be the main force of opposition
in the regional councils in
France, an opposition which will

04:27.834 --> 04:33.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be constructive, but demanding,
because we are free of any
associations, an imaginative

04:33.039 --> 04:36.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opposition, because we are
free of any interest groups.

04:36.610 --> 04:41.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The
anti-immigration National Front
Party had recently seen a rise
in popularity

04:41.314 --> 04:44.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the wake of last month's
deadly Paris attacks.

04:44.718 --> 04:50.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In Saudi Arabia, at
least 20 women won seats on
local councils following the

04:50.490 --> 04:56.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ultra-conservative kingdom's
first election open to female
candidates and voters; 2,100

04:56.730 --> 05:01.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seats were up for grabs in
Saturday's vote, but Saudi women
are still banned from driving

05:01.301 --> 05:06.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or making important decisions
without the approval of a male
relative.

05:06.072 --> 05:10.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Back in this
country, Army Sergeant Bowe
Bergdahl will face charges of

05:10.443 --> 05:15.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
desertion and endangering his
fellow troops in a
court-martial. Bergdahl walked
off his

05:15.448 --> 05:21.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
post in Eastern Afghanistan in
2009. He was held captive by the
Taliban for five years

05:21.688 --> 05:26.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
before being traded for five of
the group's leaders in
Guantanamo Bay. He now faces the

05:26.159 --> 05:29.196 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
possibility of life in prison.

05:29.196 --> 05:34.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: A Baltimore jury
today began deliberating the
fate of the first police officer
to stand

05:34.668 --> 05:39.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trial in the death of Freddie
Gray. Officer William Porter was
in the police van where

05:39.039 --> 05:43.210 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Gray sustained his
fatal neck injury.

05:43.210 --> 05:48.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In closing arguments,
prosecutors argued Porter should
have properly secured Gray in
the vehicle.

05:48.315 --> 05:53.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But his defense said there is no
evidence Porter's actions caused
Gray's death.

05:53.420 --> 05:58.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Shrimp peeled by
enslaved migrant workers and
children in Thailand have made

05:58.792 --> 06:03.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their way to all 50 states. An
Associated Press investigation
found the seafood for

06:03.897 --> 06:10.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sale at major retailers like
Wal-Mart and Whole Foods, and on
the menu at Red Lobster

06:10.103 --> 06:16.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Olive Garden. The laborers
were often held against their
will in unsanitary conditions

06:16.743 --> 06:21.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and paid little to no wages.
Many of the American businesses
are now condemning the labor
abuse

06:21.514 --> 06:24.117 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and vowing to investigate.

06:24.117 --> 06:29.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Most recreational
drones will soon be required to
register with the Federal

06:29.389 --> 06:34.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Aviation Administration. The
agency announced that today,
just in time for the holiday
gift-giving

06:34.794 --> 06:39.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
season. Remote-controlled
aircraft weighing between
half-a-pound and 55 pounds can
be

06:39.599 --> 06:44.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
registered on the FAA's Web site
beginning December 21st. That
will help authorities

06:44.904 --> 06:48.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
track down an owner if a drone
collides with another aircraft
or ventures too close to

06:48.642 --> 06:50.910 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
an airport.

06:50.910 --> 06:55.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stocks closed
higher on Wall Street today,
boosted in part by strong gains

06:55.982 --> 07:03.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the oil industry. The Dow
Jones industrial average gained
103 points to close at 17368.

07:03.423 --> 07:08.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Nasdaq rose nearly 19
points, and the S&amp;P 500 added
more than nine.

07:08.595 --> 07:14.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Still to come on the
"NewsHour": Will the historic
climate accord lead to historic

07:14.067 --> 07:20.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
results?; the GOP tries to win
the Latino vote; a migrant
bottleneck forms in Greece;

07:20.340 --> 07:28.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and a former college dean's take
on why over-involved parents
could be hurting their kids'
futures.

07:28.915 --> 07:41.728 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: U.N.
Secretary-General Ban Ki-Moon
invited world leaders today to
come

07:41.728 --> 07:46.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to New York this April to put
their signatures on a historic
climate accord.

07:46.900 --> 07:52.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there are numerous questions
about its practical realities.
Six years after a summit

07:52.005 --> 07:57.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Copenhagen failed to find
common ground, the Paris meeting
ended with a major blueprint

07:57.243 --> 08:02.849 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for governments and a
message to business.

08:02.849 --> 08:06.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Delegates from 195 countries
were on their feet after they
struck a landmark climate

08:06.720 --> 08:08.988 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
deal in Paris.

08:08.988 --> 08:11.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LAURENT FABIUS, French Foreign
Minister (through translator):
It's a small hammer, but I think

08:11.658 --> 08:13.193 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it will do great things.

08:13.193 --> 08:16.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

08:16.129 --> 08:20.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: French Foreign
Minister Laurent Fabius,
president of the conference,
gaveled

08:20.300 --> 08:23.803 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the deal to extensive applause.

08:23.803 --> 08:29.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the U.N.'s climate chief, it
was a moment of success after
six years of failure.

08:29.709 --> 08:30.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTIANA FIGUERES, Executive
Secretary, United Nations
Framework Convention on Climate

08:30.510 --> 08:37.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Change: I have been saying for a
long time, we must, we can. And
I used to say, we will.

08:37.650 --> 08:41.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Today, we can say, we did.

08:41.488 --> 08:46.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As delegates left
the conference, they cheered the
news and looked for the man

08:46.626 --> 08:51.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the hour, Laurent Fabius,
for autographs and pictures.

08:51.331 --> 08:56.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The agreement lays out a number
of goals and timelines,
including keeping the global
temperature

08:56.903 --> 09:05.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rise well below 6.3 degrees
Fahrenheit. After 2050, manmade
emissions should be reduced

09:05.245 --> 09:11.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to a level that forests and
oceans can absorb. Wealthy
countries are encouraged, but
not

09:11.217 --> 09:17.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
required to help poorer ones cut
emissions, to the tune of
pledging at least $100 billion

09:17.924 --> 09:24.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a year. And nations have to
report on their emissions and
efforts to reduce them.

09:24.631 --> 09:29.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hours after the Paris pact,
President Obama chimed in his
praise from Washington.

09:29.202 --> 09:32.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: The Paris
agreement establishes the
enduring

09:32.839 --> 09:39.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
framework the world needs to
solve the climate crisis. It
creates the mechanism, the
architecture

09:39.312 --> 09:44.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for us to continually tackle
this problem in an effective
way.

09:44.684 --> 09:50.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Even so, critics
of the deal still abound. In
Paris, some protesters said

09:50.690 --> 09:54.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this agreement doesn't go far
enough, citing no penalties for
countries that don't meet

09:54.761 --> 09:57.464 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their targets.

09:57.464 --> 10:04.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And back in the U.S.,
Republicans in Congress warned
the deal will be shredded in 13
months

10:04.270 --> 10:10.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if a Republican is elected
president. Utilities and some
Republican politicians are also
challenging

10:10.076 --> 10:14.247 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
emissions regulations in court.

10:14.247 --> 10:19.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, how meaningful are this
weekend's pledges? And does it
signal a fundamental change in

10:19.052 --> 10:22.322 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
how we will get our energy?

10:22.322 --> 10:27.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fred Krupp is the president of
the Environmental Defense Fund.
He's back from Paris. And Robert

10:27.627 --> 10:31.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bryce is a senior fellow at the
Manhattan Institute and the
author of several books

10:31.865 --> 10:37.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about this. His latest is titled
"Smaller, Faster, Lighter,
Denser, Cheaper."

10:37.136 --> 10:40.740 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we welcome you
both to the program.

10:40.740 --> 10:44.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fred Krupp, to you first. How
much of a difference is this
agreement going to make?

10:44.911 --> 10:47.614 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
FRED KRUPP, President,
Environmental Defense Fund: It's
going to make a big difference.

10:47.614 --> 10:53.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's really the first COP that
exceeded the expectations that I
had going into it, the

10:53.853 --> 10:59.859 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first conference of the parties
that really set us on a path
toward solving this problem.

10:59.859 --> 11:05.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, Judy, it doesn't solve the
climate problem. No one meeting
could do that, not by a long

11:05.431 --> 11:11.237 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shot, but it does get us a long
way there. The reductions that
have been pledged by nearly

11:11.237 --> 11:17.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
every country on Earth get us
perhaps halfway there. And then
there is a mechanism built

11:17.377 --> 11:22.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the agreement that allows
the ambitions to be ratcheted
up.

11:22.215 --> 11:28.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, perhaps most important,
there is transparency, which
means countries will have to be
reporting

11:28.922 --> 11:34.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their emissions, and there will
be a technical review of those
reports to make sure they're

11:34.027 --> 11:39.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
accurate. And that is critical,
so that there is not only
ambition here, but also
accountability.

11:39.098 --> 11:42.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Robert Bryce, do
you this as an agreement that
goes a long way toward doing

11:42.902 --> 11:44.571 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
something about climate change?

11:44.571 --> 11:47.073 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROBERT BRYCE, Senior Fellow,
Manhattan Institute: I do not.

11:47.073 --> 11:52.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there are three key
problems with it, Judy. First
is, none of these targets

11:52.011 --> 11:57.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that have been set by the
individual countries are legally
binding. Second, Ban Ki-Moon,

11:57.817 --> 12:02.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the U.N. secretary-general, made
this clear before the meeting
started in Paris when he

12:02.755 --> 12:08.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
said that all of these targets
that have been made by the
individual countries are not
sufficient,

12:08.027 --> 12:10.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that they're going to have
to come back in just a few years
and provide new lower

12:10.997 --> 12:13.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
targets for emissions.

12:13.333 --> 12:17.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, finally, and perhaps most
importantly, there is nothing in
any of these agreements

12:17.870 --> 12:23.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that moves the ball forward on
nuclear energy, and this is the
key issue. When you listen

12:23.376 --> 12:28.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to what the climate scientists
have been saying on this, on
December 3, in The Guardian,
James

12:28.181 --> 12:33.219 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Hansen, one of the most
high-profile climate scientists
in the world, along with three

12:33.219 --> 12:38.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other climate scientists, said
that nuclear energy will make
the difference -- I'm quoting

12:38.291 --> 12:41.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- "make the difference between
the world missing crucial
climate targets or achieving

12:41.160 --> 12:43.496 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them."

12:43.496 --> 12:48.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the hard reality is that,
unless we have an energy form
that can replace substantial

12:48.768 --> 12:53.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
quantities of coal-fired
generation -- and that means
natural gas and nuclear -- then

12:53.406 --> 12:58.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that we're not going to
come near any kind of
significant reductions in CO2

12:58.678 --> 13:03.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
emissions to meet the CO2
emissions targets that have been
laid out.

13:03.282 --> 13:08.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, Fred Krupp,
let me take his -- Mr. Bryce's
last point first, that

13:08.888 --> 13:14.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the agreement doesn't make
meaningful progress on moving
toward nuclear or another real
alternative

13:14.293 --> 13:16.162 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to carbon.

13:16.162 --> 13:20.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED KRUPP: Well, I would
strongly disagree with that.

13:20.566 --> 13:27.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Countries are free to meet their
obligations any way they want
to, but they have to report

13:27.073 --> 13:32.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and be accountable, as I said
before. China plans to build 30
nuclear power plants and

13:32.812 --> 13:39.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is constructing about half that
number now. So, if nuclear
technology comes along that's

13:39.852 --> 13:45.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
safe and affordable, nuclear
very much is on the table and
could be part of the agreement.

13:45.358 --> 13:47.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, Fred Krupp,
there is no requirement that
countries do that. Is that

13:47.960 --> 13:50.063 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
correct?

13:50.063 --> 13:53.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED KRUPP: Well, there is no
requirement that countries use
nuclear, no. They're free

13:53.232 --> 13:57.370 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
to use whatever
technology they choose.

13:57.370 --> 14:04.444 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But some countries are pursuing
nuclear, and that's allowed. It
turns out, Judy, that the

14:04.444 --> 14:10.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cost of solar panels in the last
five years has dropped 80
percent. So, if solar panels

14:10.950 --> 14:18.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are cheaper than nuclear, why
should the -- an agreement
require countries to use
nuclear?

14:18.224 --> 14:21.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nuclear may end up cheaper. That
remains to be seen. Right now,
the plants that are being

14:21.894 --> 14:28.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
built in the United States will
substantially raise the rates of
rate payers in the jurisdictions

14:28.534 --> 14:31.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where those are being built,
because, right now, it is an
expensive technology, at least

14:31.804 --> 14:34.040 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
here in the U.S.

14:34.040 --> 14:40.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Robert Bryce, why
isn't it sufficient, if not --
even the advocates of

14:40.480 --> 14:44.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this agreement are saying it's
not perfect, but why isn't it
sufficient that countries

14:44.484 --> 14:47.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are now saying they're going to
move in the direction, not all
necessarily nuclear, but

14:47.887 --> 14:51.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these other technologies,
alternative fuel technologies?

14:51.324 --> 14:53.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT BRYCE: Sure. And we hear
about solar and wind. And we
have heard about solar and

14:53.059 --> 14:55.161 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wind.

14:55.161 --> 15:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, look, I'm pro-solar. I have
solar panels on the roof of my
house. I'm not bullish on

15:01.300 --> 15:05.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wind, because it takes up too
much land. The problem,
fundamentally, for the
developing

15:05.138 --> 15:07.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
world is that they're not
turning to solar and wind in a
big way. They're turning to

15:07.874 --> 15:11.144 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
coal-fired capacity.

15:11.144 --> 15:15.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's look at the numbers that
have been published by Sierra
Club and CoalSwarm, two adamant

15:15.414 --> 15:22.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
coal critics. They point out
that, today, there is 276
gigawatts of coal-fired capacity

15:22.622 --> 15:26.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
under construction now. That's
roughly equal to the entire
coal-fired capacity of the
United

15:26.325 --> 15:28.661 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

15:28.661 --> 15:32.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Krupp says we have to make
nuclear safer and cheaper.
There's no question. But to make

15:32.665 --> 15:37.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that happen, we have to have
strong governmental leadership.
I have written many times about

15:37.303 --> 15:41.140 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this. I had a piece in The L.A.
Times just a few days ago. The
United States could be

15:41.140 --> 15:44.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
taking a leadership position in
making nuclear energy safer,
cheaper, developing reactors

15:44.777 --> 15:47.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that are passively safe.

15:47.480 --> 15:51.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we don't have the support --
this is key -- of the main
environmental groups, including

15:51.951 --> 15:54.620 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Environmental Defense Fund.
Sierra Club and Green Peace are
adamantly opposed to nuclear

15:54.620 --> 15:54.854 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
energy.

15:54.854 --> 15:55.454 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

15:55.454 --> 15:55.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All
right. Excuse me.

15:55.922 --> 15:57.156 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT BRYCE: Sure.

15:57.156 --> 15:59.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I'm sorry for
interrupting, but let me let Mr.
Krupp respond.

15:59.759 --> 16:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED KRUPP: First of all, we're
not opposed to nuclear energy.

16:03.529 --> 16:10.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Second of all, the statistics
about 276 plants, those were
statistics from a few years ago.

16:10.469 --> 16:16.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was planned, not under
construction. But we had a lot
of plants planned in the

16:16.108 --> 16:22.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
United States just a few short
years ago, and they have almost
all, to a one, been scrapped.

16:22.081 --> 16:27.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, India's plans to build
coal-fired plants -- change will
come to India, because it's

16:27.086 --> 16:31.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in their own national interest.
Sure, they have to lift people
out of poverty. They need

16:31.657 --> 16:37.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
electricity. They need economic
development, but they also need
clean air. Right now, they

16:37.230 --> 16:46.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have more opportunities than
ever before to create jobs with
renewable energy and to have

16:46.038 --> 16:51.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
clean air. The air pollution is
killing hundreds of thousands of
people a year in India.

16:51.143 --> 16:57.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So all I would say, Mr. Bryce,
to you is that no one predicted
how fast natural gas came

16:57.350 --> 17:02.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
online in the United States. It
was a big change. And the change
we're seeing now that

17:02.655 --> 17:07.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think will surprise a lot of
people is how fast the cost of
these clean energy technologies

17:07.927 --> 17:10.596 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are coming down.

17:10.596 --> 17:12.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
gentlemen, big subject. We are
clearly going to be coming back
to

17:12.865 --> 17:15.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it a lot in the future.

17:15.234 --> 17:18.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I want to thank both of you,
Fred Krupp, Robert Bryce. Thank
you.

17:18.137 --> 17:22.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT BRYCE: Thank you.

17:22.775 --> 17:28.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
FRED KRUPP: Thank you.

17:28.814 --> 17:34.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It's Politics
Monday, and we have two takes
this week on an increasingly
competitive

17:34.053 --> 17:36.622 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
presidential race.

17:36.622 --> 17:41.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As Republicans prepare to debate
tomorrow night in Las Vegas,
religion and immigration

17:41.427 --> 17:46.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have emerged as running themes.
But are GOP candidates, led by
front-runner Donald Trump,

17:46.732 --> 17:50.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doing more harm than good when
it comes to expanding the
party's base among a growing

17:50.036 --> 17:53.539 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
subset of Hispanic voters?

17:53.539 --> 17:58.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
William Brangham traveled to
Washington State recently to
explore one effort, bankrolled

17:58.044 --> 18:04.150 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
by the billionaire Koch
brothers, to recruit Hispanics
into the GOP's tent.

18:04.150 --> 18:09.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It's election
night, and Avina Gutierrez just
made history. For the

18:09.822 --> 18:14.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first time ever, voters in
Yakima, Washington, elected a
Hispanic candidate to their city

18:14.560 --> 18:19.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
council, not just one, in fact.
Three Latinos won seats tonight,
this in a city where 40

18:19.298 --> 18:22.601 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
percent of residents
are Hispanic.

18:22.601 --> 18:25.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The 35-year-old Democrat says
tonight's victory is just
another sign of the growing
presence

18:25.938 --> 18:28.507 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Latinos in politics.

18:28.507 --> 18:30.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AVINA GUTIERREZ, Yakima City
Council Member: Tonight means
that I will be able to provide

18:30.476 --> 18:34.413 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an example for other Latinas to
see that they do have a seat at
that table.

18:34.413 --> 18:38.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Her election
is part of a national trend. The
Latino population of

18:38.351 --> 18:42.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the U.S. has been steadily
rising, while the white
population has been declining.

18:42.955 --> 18:49.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By 2065, the U.S. is projected
to be a majority-minority
nation, with whites making up
less than half

18:49.628 --> 18:55.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the population. Politically,
this trajectory has been great
news for Democrats like
Gutierrez.

18:55.401 --> 19:02.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In national polls, Latinos lean
Democratic more than 2-1 over
Republicans. And, in 2012,

19:02.408 --> 19:06.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Latinos overwhelmingly picked
President Obama over Mitt
Romney, whose remarks about
Latinos

19:06.145 --> 19:10.449 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
needing to self-deport
didn't sit well with many.

19:10.449 --> 19:15.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In its own political autopsy of
that election, the Republican
National Committee openly
acknowledged

19:15.721 --> 19:20.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that if the party couldn't
figure out a better way to
communicate with Latino voters,
it

19:20.426 --> 19:26.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would spell electoral doom for
the GOP -- quote -- "It does not
matter what we say about
education,

19:26.732 --> 19:29.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
jobs or the economy. If
Hispanics think we do not want
them here, they will close their

19:29.935 --> 19:37.276 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ears to our policies."

19:37.276 --> 19:41.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's where Daniel Garza
comes in. He's the head of The
LIBRE Initiative. It's the

19:41.447 --> 19:46.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
largest conservative Hispanic
political group in the country.
And he's just been given $16

19:46.552 --> 19:51.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
million from the conservative
billionaire Koch brothers to try
and convince Latinos

19:51.057 --> 19:55.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that conservative ideals and
Latino ideals are one and the
same.

19:55.528 --> 19:59.331 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL GARZA, The LIBRE
Initiative: We are driving a
conversation within the Latino
community

19:59.331 --> 20:05.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about the virtues of the free
market, whether it's engaging
them on policy issues or on

20:05.071 --> 20:09.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
cultural issues. So, for
example, we believe strongly in
self-reliance, in personal
responsibility,

20:09.809 --> 20:13.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in that hard work ethic, the
American rugged individualism.

20:13.412 --> 20:16.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Garza served
in George W. Bush's White House,
and now regularly hosts

20:16.782 --> 20:20.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
forums with today's
GOP candidates.

20:20.753 --> 20:25.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But his story begins much more
humbly, here, in the
agriculturally-rich Yakima
Valley in

20:25.458 --> 20:30.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Central Washington. The Hispanic
population has exploded here in
recent decades, as migrant

20:30.796 --> 20:34.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
families like Garza's, who once
just came through to pick apples
and cherries during

20:34.733 --> 20:39.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the harvest, decided to
stay and put down roots.

20:39.405 --> 20:41.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Garza showed us the hops fields
-- they're now out of season --
where he and his family

20:41.540 --> 20:43.642 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
used to work.

20:43.642 --> 20:48.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL GARZA: Backbreaking work,
working in the elements. Didn't
pay hardly anything,

20:48.013 --> 20:51.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and you were powerless. And I
don't know of any mother who
says, I can't wait for my child

20:51.250 --> 20:56.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to grow up to be a farm worker.
It just doesn't happen. But it's
noble work.

20:56.655 --> 21:00.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: They lived in
nearby Toppenish, Washington,
population 9,000, in this little

21:00.626 --> 21:03.395 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
house with no running water.

21:03.395 --> 21:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL GARZA: The idea, as farm
workers, is that you rent the
cheapest home you can.

21:07.600 --> 21:12.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It was,
admittedly, a tough life. But
Garza's dad was able to save up

21:12.204 --> 21:16.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his money and eventually buy
this small motel in town.

21:16.509 --> 21:21.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was this step up the economic
ladder where young Daniel began
finding his political beliefs.

21:21.680 --> 21:25.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He became a cop. He took a job
working for the hard-charging
Republican Congressman Doc

21:25.951 --> 21:30.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hastings. He was a huge fan of
William F. Buckley on "Firing
Line." It all made sense

21:30.956 --> 21:34.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to him, and he became a
card-carrying member of the
Republican Party.

21:34.460 --> 21:39.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL GARZA: You know, I sort
of was taken by Ronald Reagan's
approach to governance

21:39.665 --> 21:42.568 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and sort of embraced it.

21:42.568 --> 21:45.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Reagan
famously said that Hispanics are
conservatives; they just don't

21:45.237 --> 21:45.838 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
know it yet.

21:45.838 --> 21:47.873 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, do you believe that?

21:47.873 --> 21:50.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL GARZA: I do. I do believe
that. And I have always believed
that they embrace the

21:50.809 --> 21:53.979 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ideals of the free market.

21:53.979 --> 21:59.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And that's the
message The LIBRE Initiative is
pushing today, with slickly

21:59.552 --> 22:05.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
produced videos starring Garza
using his rags-to-riches story
as a symbol of conservative
Latino empowerment.

22:05.591 --> 22:08.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIEL GARZA: My father never
took welfare because he didn't
want to depend on anyone

22:08.027 --> 22:11.130 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or lose his dignity.

22:11.130 --> 22:20.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: They're also
spreading their message in more
subtle ways. This is actually

22:20.339 --> 22:24.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a driver's education class run
by Garza's group. This one's in
Las Vegas, but they do

22:24.944 --> 22:30.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
these in swing states all over
the U.S. The idea is, you draw
Latinos in for useful classes

22:30.549 --> 22:34.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like these -- they also teach
English-language classes and
help prepare tax returns.

22:34.587 --> 22:37.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And while they're there, those
voters get a little dose of
conservative politics on

22:37.823 --> 22:39.925 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the side.

22:39.925 --> 22:44.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL GARZA: I would say, we
use that opportunity as a
platform for ourselves to drive
our ideas,

22:44.797 --> 22:48.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to talk to folks and connect
with them. And then, you know,
if it resonates with them,

22:48.467 --> 22:52.404 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
then they join our effort and
they stay connected with us.

22:52.404 --> 22:56.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Garza's group
collects contact information at
these events for themselves,

22:56.075 --> 23:00.346 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which it then shares with a
group called i360, a massive
voter database operation funded

23:00.346 --> 23:03.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
by the Koch brothers' network.

23:03.515 --> 23:07.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For LIBRE, the hope is that
these events, with their focus
on economic liberty and family

23:07.219 --> 23:09.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
values, will resonate
with Latino voters.

