race now basically come down to
three, maybe four people. And

32:22.607 --> 32:26.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it's Donald Trump and it's Ted
Cruz and it's Marco Rubio.

32:26.611 --> 32:29.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The one person who I think is
sort of on the bubble right now
is Chris Christie, who is

32:29.981 --> 32:33.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doing better in New Hampshire.
And I think this environment
that we're in right now,

32:33.985 --> 32:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one where terrorism and security
is the top of the mind for
voters, especially Republican

32:37.455 --> 32:41.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
voters, that plays well
to Christie's strengths.

32:41.359 --> 32:46.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think he will be making
that case a lot tomorrow night,
and making that distinction

32:46.198 --> 32:53.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
between himself, governor in New
Jersey, been around during
terrorism strikes, I know how

32:53.238 --> 32:55.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to deal with this, these other
guys don't know what they're
doing.

32:55.407 --> 32:59.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: How does Marco Rubio
distinguish himself in that kind
of field?

32:59.211 --> 33:01.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: I think that there
is more pressure on Marco Rubio
heading into this debate than

33:01.980 --> 33:04.850 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
there have been in past debates.

33:04.850 --> 33:10.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's continually had a strong
debate performance, but now
people are sort of expecting him
to

33:10.822 --> 33:14.159 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have a strong debate
performance. And so I think a
lot of people will be watching
him

33:14.159 --> 33:19.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for that performance. The
question, though, is, he has
these good debate performances,

33:19.431 --> 33:23.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then there is this buzz, and
then he maybe moves up a couple
points. He doesn't have

33:23.101 --> 33:25.971 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the big surge that Ted Cruz has.

33:25.971 --> 33:33.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In part, that is because Ted
Cruz is competing on the
anti-establishment, Tea Party,
evangelical

33:33.545 --> 33:37.048 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
side, and Marco Rubio is
competing on the other side of
the Republican Party, the
establishment

33:37.048 --> 33:40.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
side, which is a very crowded
neighborhood right now.

33:40.518 --> 33:44.856 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: And I think,
ultimately, the winner is going
to be the person, like Ted Cruz,

33:44.856 --> 33:50.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
who is an establishment
candidate, but puts themselves
as anti-establishment.

33:50.061 --> 33:53.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ted Cruz is a member of the
United States Senate, has been
part of the Bush administration

33:53.798 --> 33:55.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in his past, but now
is running against...

33:55.066 --> 33:56.635 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

33:56.635 --> 34:01.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: I'm going to be
watching Ben Carson to see if he
can break out, or anybody else

34:01.306 --> 34:03.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the fringes. It's going to be
-- I think it's going to be very
interesting.

34:03.041 --> 34:04.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: It will be
interesting, I don't doubt.

34:04.376 --> 34:06.578 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Call me.

34:06.578 --> 34:11.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Amy Walter, Tamara Keith,
thank you both very much.

34:11.149 --> 34:18.023 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: You're welcome.

34:18.023 --> 34:23.828 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And
now to overseas.

34:23.828 --> 34:28.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Greek Prime Minister Alexis
Tsipras says that he will not
allow his country to become what

34:28.867 --> 34:34.539 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
he calls a warehouse for
refugees. And Europe's border
agency is expected to send
agents to

34:34.539 --> 34:39.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Greece soon in an attempt to
stem the inflow of migrants.

34:39.477 --> 34:44.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Currently, refugees from only
the conflicts in Syria,
Afghanistan and Iraq are being
permitted

34:44.416 --> 34:48.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to transit Greece to
countries farther north.

34:48.353 --> 34:53.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, as special correspondent
Malcolm Brabant reports, there's
now a roadblock on that trail,

34:53.758 --> 34:58.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leaving many migrants from other
countries with some tough
choices.

34:58.330 --> 35:04.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Spanish
lifeguards respond to a call
from volunteers scanning the
horizon

35:04.269 --> 35:07.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the cliffs of Lesbos. They're
heading out to the channel to
shepherd the flimsy inflatables

35:07.739 --> 35:11.476 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to safety.

35:11.476 --> 35:16.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
After several rough days
prevented crossings from Turkey,
the seas are calm. A flotilla

35:16.581 --> 35:21.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of overcrowded rubber dinghies
is using the shortest crossing
between the two countries.

35:21.353 --> 35:27.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The occupants have paid $1,000 a
head for the journey. In the
distorted economics of

35:27.292 --> 35:30.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the migrant trail, safe arrival
represents value for money,
especially for Syrians like

35:30.795 --> 35:33.365 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hamza Hussein.

35:33.365 --> 35:40.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAMZA HUSSEIN, Refugee: You need
to kill Bashar. They are killing
people now. I am too -- I

35:40.472 --> 35:45.110 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
can't speak now,
please. Thank you.

35:45.110 --> 35:49.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: In the middle
of the picture, you can see a
lifeguard trying to help a
refugee

35:49.581 --> 35:55.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who has plunged into the sea 50
meters off shore. Mohammed Asti
Mimi is an Iraqi, given

35:55.854 --> 35:59.824 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
priority by Europe in the
new two-tier migrant trail.

35:59.824 --> 36:04.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOHAMMED ASTI MIMI, Refugee:
Yes, I have been swimming. I
have been swimming, because I

36:04.262 --> 36:07.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
thought was funny,
jumped into water.

36:07.766 --> 36:12.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Having secured
a foothold in Europe, the
Syrians, Afghans and Iraqis

36:12.637 --> 36:18.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are assured of a relatively
swift passage to the destination
of their choice. But all

36:18.610 --> 36:24.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other nationalities on this
beach have arrived as the gates
have shut, after Greece's
neighbor,

36:24.015 --> 36:30.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Macedonia, said it would only
admit people from these three
conflicts.

36:30.288 --> 36:35.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Farmer Costas Bayotis, who helps
the refugees ashore and salvages
the rafts' components,

36:35.260 --> 36:39.364 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
disapproves of what he believes
is a discriminatory system.

36:39.364 --> 36:45.236 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
COSTAS BAYOTIS, Farmer (through
translator): In my opinion, all
the world is suffering.

36:45.236 --> 36:49.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they're from Afghanistan,
Iran, Iraq, or Bangladesh, they
are all in the same situation

36:49.974 --> 36:54.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and must be helped. They have
all got souls. The politicians
are more educated than we

36:54.579 --> 36:57.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are, so let them try and come up
with a solution for a better
tomorrow for these people, the

36:57.982 --> 37:00.151 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
best possible.

37:00.151 --> 37:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Dawn at the
next step on the migrant trail,
Piraeus, the country's

37:05.690 --> 37:10.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
key port on the mainland, where,
daily, ferries arrive carrying
thousands of people, aiming

37:10.428 --> 37:14.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to pass through Greece
as quickly as possible.

37:14.566 --> 37:22.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The intention of most is to
travel more than 300 miles north
to Macedonia. At the ramps,

37:22.073 --> 37:25.543 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
scores of travel agents offer
bus tickets to the border.

37:25.543 --> 37:30.715 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Macedonia. Macedonia.

37:30.715 --> 37:37.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But this is the
ultimate destination for those
who are not Syrian,

37:37.388 --> 37:42.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Iraqi or Afghan: a fenced-off
former Olympic martial arts
stadium in Athens. All other

37:42.994 --> 37:47.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
nationalities have been
transported here after last
week's closure by Greece of a
camp at

37:47.031 --> 37:50.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Idomeni on the border
with Macedonia.

37:50.502 --> 37:54.772 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Food is in short supply, and
volunteers have struggled to
pacify the newcomers.

37:54.772 --> 37:58.143 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: We are here to help you.

37:58.143 --> 37:57.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: "We are here to
help you," called out a
volunteer, urging everyone to

37:57.876 --> 37:59.310 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
stay calm.

37:59.310 --> 38:03.515 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Help us. Don't push.

38:03.515 --> 38:08.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: It's been a
venue for violence, stabbing,
protests and arrests.

38:08.353 --> 38:13.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: Conditions are a problem.
There is a sleeping problem.
There is a food problem.

38:13.725 --> 38:16.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a big line. That people
are from Morocco and all these
countries. Yes, the fighting

38:16.294 --> 38:21.032 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is a problem.

38:21.032 --> 38:27.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Outside the
stadium, we met 22-year old
Tassdaq Hussain from Pakistan,

38:27.972 --> 38:31.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one of those deported from
Idomeni last week, when Greece
acknowledged that Macedonia
wouldn't

38:31.643 --> 38:34.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
compromise over its
wide-ranging ban.

38:34.946 --> 38:40.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TASSDAQ HUSSAIN, Refugee: But
now I have no idea how to go to
Germany and other countries,

38:40.919 --> 38:49.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because this border is sealed
for us and Iranians and some
countries. We request to
European

38:49.661 --> 38:54.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Union and other countries, help
us and please try to open the
border for us.

38:54.832 --> 38:59.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: In common with
other excluded nationalities,
Hussain's options are to seek

38:59.904 --> 39:05.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
asylum in Greece, leave the
country within 30 days, or be
repatriated with a small
financial

39:05.310 --> 39:07.212 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
grant.

39:07.212 --> 39:10.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the government gives you
money to go back, will you go
back?

39:10.615 --> 39:15.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TASSDAQ HUSSAIN: How much money
do they give? We have spent more
than $4,000, more than

39:15.687 --> 39:30.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
$4,000. They give us 400 euros.
This is too much -- little. This
is the main problem.

39:30.668 --> 39:37.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many People have sold all his
fields, his animals, his house,
and like this. They have

39:37.875 --> 39:44.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no business here. If they have
good -- why come here? If
anybody is comfortable in their

39:44.115 --> 39:48.786 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
country and their
homeland, why come here?

39:48.786 --> 39:53.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: In the Greek
Parliament, Prime Minister
Alexis Tsipras, once a supporter

39:53.858 --> 39:58.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of open borders, made it clear
that times have changed, as a
result of Macedonia's ban

39:58.263 --> 40:00.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and European pressure.

40:00.732 --> 40:04.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALEXIS TSIPRAS, Greek Prime
Minister (through translator):
It is true that, if this influx

40:04.936 --> 40:09.774 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
continues, there is a danger for
the country to be turned into a
warehouse for immigrants.

40:09.774 --> 40:14.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, the country must not and
will not become a warehouse. We
welcome the establishment

40:14.545 --> 40:19.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of a European Coast Guard. It is
welcome, and the Greek forces
will contribute.

40:19.017 --> 40:23.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Europe's
reinforcements will arrive at a
time when Turkey is supposed to

40:23.454 --> 40:28.159 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
be stemming the flow of
migrants, in return for more
than $3 billion and a promise to

40:28.159 --> 40:31.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
speed up the process
of joining the E.U.

40:31.963 --> 40:36.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the large number of boats
landing in Lesbos has left some
analysts like Ioannis
Papageorgiou

40:36.934 --> 40:39.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
wondering what Turkey
is doing for its money.

40:39.937 --> 40:42.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
IOANNIS PAPAGEORGIOU, Political
Scientist: I think it's a
disgrace that we have to suffer

40:42.940 --> 40:49.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- suffer blackmail from Turkey
as the European Union, but it's
realpolitik. I'm not sure

40:49.147 --> 40:54.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they will be able to
fulfill their side of the
bargain. And I'm not also sure
that

40:54.852 --> 40:58.122 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the European Union will fulfill
its side of the bargain either.

40:58.122 --> 41:03.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Many of those
people now arriving in Lesbos
face real frustration,

41:03.127 --> 41:07.031 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because it looks as though the
migrant trail has been severed.

41:07.031 --> 41:12.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Greece's neighbors, Macedonia
and Bulgaria, are effectively
blocked. And the only other

41:12.403 --> 41:18.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
possible available route over
land is Albania. Now, that
nation is mountainous. It's
freezing

41:18.343 --> 41:24.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cold in winter, and overall is
much more dangerous than any
other Balkan country. But the
traffickers

41:24.048 --> 41:27.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are considering opening that up
as the next possible option,
even though they're well

41:27.819 --> 41:32.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
aware that people may
possibly die there.

41:32.890 --> 41:38.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, having survived the game of
Russian roulette that is the sea
crossing from Turkey, the

41:38.629 --> 41:43.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
refugees have become used to
making calculated risks. The
hope of finding safe haven and

41:43.768 --> 41:48.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
relative prosperity keeps
driving this historic movement
of humanity.

41:48.406 --> 41:55.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant in Lesbos.

41:55.713 --> 42:11.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Next: Olive oil is a
staple in many of America's
kitchens, and much of it

42:11.329 --> 42:15.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is produced in Italy. But a
mysterious infection is now
threatening that industry and a
way

42:15.466 --> 42:17.769 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of life.

42:17.769 --> 42:22.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown recently traveled
to the olive groves of Southern
Italy.

42:22.006 --> 42:27.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's the heel of
Italy's boot. The Salento region
may be less known than

42:27.812 --> 42:33.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the country's more famous
tourist areas. But it boasts
beautiful port towns and idyllic

42:33.418 --> 42:38.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
country roads lined with farms,
vineyards and, most of all, its
renowned olive groves,

42:38.756 --> 42:41.192 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
some thousands of years old.

42:41.192 --> 42:43.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIOVANNI MELCARNE, Oliver Grower
(through translator): For us,
these are not only trees

42:43.628 --> 42:46.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that produce olive oil, but they
are the Salento landscape
itself. Without these trees, the

42:46.531 --> 42:49.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Salento will no longer exist.

42:49.000 --> 42:55.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A deadly bacteria
dubbed an olive Ebola has
infected someone million trees

42:55.139 --> 43:00.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so far, about 10 percent of the
trees in the larger Puglia
province. Some of those olive

43:00.211 --> 43:03.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
groves have been in
families for generations.

43:03.815 --> 43:08.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the case for Giovanni
Melcarne, a grower who believes
500 of his 5,000 trees are now

43:08.519 --> 43:10.021 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
infected.

43:10.021 --> 43:14.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But you're fairly certain that
all of this will be lost.

43:14.125 --> 43:16.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GIOVANNI MELCARNE (through
translator): By what we have
seen so far in the past few
months,

43:16.227 --> 43:18.262 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
yes.

43:18.262 --> 43:23.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The bacteria is
Xylella fastidiosa, and for
years has been found in a
variety

43:23.701 --> 43:29.674 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of plants in Brazil and
California. It is commonly known
as Pierce's disease.

43:29.674 --> 43:34.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this strain was discovered
two years ago in Italy by Donato
Boscia, a virologist at

43:34.011 --> 43:39.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the National Research Council in
Bari, while he was visiting his
father-in-law's farm.

43:39.884 --> 43:43.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONATO BOSCIA, Virologist: My
father in law said, "Donato,
please, tomorrow, we can go

43:43.187 --> 43:49.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the field. I want to show you
some abnormal -- of the olive
trees." And I went there and

43:49.894 --> 43:51.896 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I was shocked.

43:51.896 --> 43:56.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The first signs
of infection are dried-out
leaves, known as leaf scorching.

43:56.934 --> 44:02.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Eventually, the whole tree
withers. It's thought to have
come to Italy via Costa Rica,
hitching

44:02.240 --> 44:08.212 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a ride on a decorative coffee
plant. And it's spread by
insects feeding on tree tissue.

44:08.212 --> 44:15.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Boscia's team is monitoring that
spread by confirming samples,
studying its carriers,

44:15.186 --> 44:20.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and testing the live bacteria on
various olive subspecies to see
which might be resistant.

44:20.858 --> 44:26.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONATO BOSCIA: We are sure that
the only tool that we have at
the moment available to try

44:26.864 --> 44:33.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to prevent the appearance of
this disease, of this quick
decline of olive is try to
prevent

44:33.170 --> 44:36.874 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the arrival of the bacteria.

44:36.874 --> 44:41.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Italians take
their food very seriously, and
on nearly every table is a

44:41.879 --> 44:47.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bottle of good olive oil. On
average, Italy trails only Spain
in oil production, responsible

44:47.952 --> 44:52.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for 15 percent of the world's
virgin olive oil and half of
U.S. imports in an industry

44:52.823 --> 44:57.495 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that pulls in more than $2
billion a year to the country.

44:57.495 --> 45:02.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Its popularity has only grown,
as it's been touted for a range
of health benefits, including

45:02.466 --> 45:08.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reducing the risk of heart
disease. With so much at stake,
for Italy and the rest of
Europe,

45:08.339 --> 45:13.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the European Union earlier this
year established a buffer zone
to contain the bacteria to one

45:13.010 --> 45:18.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
province in the south, a
controversial move that left
many growers angry.

45:18.249 --> 45:22.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GIOVANNI MELCARNE (through
translator): We are very
dissatisfied. The E.U. is only
interested

45:22.153 --> 45:25.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in blocking the advance of the
bacteria to the north. This
area, the area of the breakout,

45:25.089 --> 45:27.858 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
has been left to its fate.

45:27.858 --> 45:31.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The measure
required the cutting down of
infected trees and even
seemingly

45:31.596 --> 45:33.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
healthy ones nearby.

45:33.965 --> 45:36.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIUSEPPE SILLETTI, Regional
Director, Italian Forestry
Service (through translator): My

45:36.067 --> 45:40.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
job would be a lot easier if not
for all the misunderstanding.
Every group has different

45:40.104 --> 45:42.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
thoughts on how to
tackle the problem.

45:42.807 --> 45:47.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Giuseppe
Silletti, regional director of
Italy's Forestry Service, is the

45:47.745 --> 45:52.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
man tasked with implementing
that plan for the Italian
government and E.U. But he says

45:52.316 --> 45:55.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he's not getting the help
he needs from farmers.

45:55.152 --> 45:58.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIUSEPPE SILLETTI (through
translator): I have news that
the owners do everything they

45:58.956 --> 46:04.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can to hide the disease. If they
have a tree with symptoms, they
prune the plants, so they

46:04.228 --> 46:07.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
look healthy. This is very bad,
because it prevents us from
being able to identify how

46:07.231 --> 46:10.167 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
much the disease is spreading.

46:10.167 --> 46:14.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In fact, many
farmers and activists are
skeptical of both the government
response

46:14.038 --> 46:17.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and the scientific
research on the bacteria.

46:17.808 --> 46:24.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Virologist Donato Boscia was
even accused of introducing the
bacteria into Italy.

46:24.015 --> 46:30.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONATO BOSCIA: Saying to these
people, sorry, but we are, how
to say, a cancer, like that,

46:30.755 --> 46:36.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so something that you can not
cure, that your time is limited,
there are -- no therapy,

46:36.127 --> 46:39.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is something that is
difficult to accept.

46:39.363 --> 46:43.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Some, like olive
grower Roberto Polo, believe a
variety of factors, including

46:43.901 --> 46:46.437 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pesticides, are to blame.

46:46.437 --> 46:49.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTO POLO, Olive Grower
(through translator): I believe
that it is not only the bacteria

46:49.907 --> 46:54.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to blame for the rapid drying
out of the olive trees, but a
combination of causes which have

46:54.111 --> 46:57.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
compromised the immune system of
the trees. In practice, we have
seen a reduction in the

46:57.948 --> 47:01.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ability of the trees to defend
themselves from external attacks
of any kind.

47:01.218 --> 47:03.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTO ZILETTI, Business Owner:
It's a matter of time. It will
come.

47:03.988 --> 47:09.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Polo's neighbor,
Roberto Ziletti, owns the Antica
Masseria del Fano, an old

47:09.927 --> 47:12.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
farm that's been converted into
a bed and breakfast with its own
prize-winning olive

47:12.797 --> 47:15.232 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
oil production.

47:15.232 --> 47:19.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTO ZILETTI: Historically,
there are people that believe
that these things always happen,

47:19.704 --> 47:22.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it will -- as it arrives,
it will go away, alone.

47:22.373 --> 47:23.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Just naturally.

47:23.774 --> 47:24.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBERTO ZILETTI: Naturally.

47:24.608 --> 47:26.911 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

47:26.911 --> 47:30.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTO ZILETTI: I don't know if
this is true. Probably, it's
true, but the matter is that

47:30.314 --> 47:33.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
these days the problem
is very, very big.

47:33.084 --> 47:37.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The government
has been attempting to enlist
more cooperation from farmers by

47:37.321 --> 47:42.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
paying them to cut down their
own infected trees. That plan
was dealt a blow last month

47:42.259 --> 47:47.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when a regional Italian court
temporarily halted the removal
of outwardly healthy trees

47:47.465 --> 47:52.236 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the infected zone, until the
bacteria could be proven as the
cause of the disease.

47:52.236 --> 47:55.106 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Researcher Boscia
responds this way:

47:55.106 --> 48:00.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONATO BOSCIA: We do not have
the proof that the bacterium
alone can cause the disease,

48:00.978 --> 48:06.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but the disease appear only when
the bacterium arrive there.

48:06.584 --> 48:10.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Also unknown is
the incubation period, meaning
many more trees could be
infected

48:10.221 --> 48:13.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and not yet symptomatic.

48:13.057 --> 48:16.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GIOVANNI MELCARNE (through
translator): In Italy, we have
100 different opinions. But

48:16.961 --> 48:20.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what is certain is that these
plants are dying, that these
plants are drying, and we don't

48:20.264 --> 48:22.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
know what the future will be.
And we don't even know that
there's a solution to this

48:22.032 --> 48:24.001 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
situation.

48:24.001 --> 48:28.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And there are
already signs the bacteria has
spread farther north, even

48:28.672 --> 48:32.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to France and Corsica, though
not yet infecting olive trees,
suggesting this problem isn't

48:32.943 --> 48:36.347 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going anywhere anytime soon.

48:36.347 --> 48:49.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From the boot of Southern Italy,
I'm Jeffrey Brown for the "PBS
NewsHour."

48:49.960 --> 49:04.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we return to
another one of our "NewsHour"
essays.

49:04.542 --> 49:11.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, Julie Lythcott-Haims, a
former Stanford University
undergraduate dean and author of

49:11.215 --> 49:15.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the book "How to Raise an
Adult," shares ideas on her
belief that the job of parents
is to

49:15.419 --> 49:18.823 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
put themselves out of work.

49:18.823 --> 49:23.527 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's her perspective on why it
is important to get out of the
overparenting trap.

49:23.527 --> 49:25.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIE LYTHCOTT-HAIMS, Author,
"How to Raise an Adult": We
parents seem to have forgotten

49:25.663 --> 49:30.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a simple, unassailable
fact: We're mammals.

49:30.467 --> 49:35.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sure, we may be mammals with
clothing and cell phones,
but,like our counterparts in

49:35.306 --> 49:41.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the wild, our job as parents is
to put ourselves out of a job,
and raise our kids to be
independent

49:41.579 --> 49:45.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
adults who can raise their own
offspring one day. If you think
about it, it's how we evolved

49:45.783 --> 49:48.586 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to this point as humans.

49:48.586 --> 49:54.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, these days, too many of us
feel our child simply will not
be successful in life unless

49:54.358 --> 49:58.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we constantly protect and
prevent at every turn, hover
over every happening,
micromanage

49:58.629 --> 50:03.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
every moment, take care
of every little thing.

50:03.267 --> 50:08.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, we can help our kids get a
short-term win when we overhelp,
such as the better grades

50:08.272 --> 50:12.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that come when we remind them to
put their homework in their
backpack, or bring it to

50:12.042 --> 50:17.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
school when they have forgotten
it, or outright do some of the
work for them.

50:17.448 --> 50:21.919 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And our overinvolvement
certainly makes life more
pleasant for our kids. Often, we
let

50:21.919 --> 50:26.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them off the hook for doing the
mundane tasks of life, such as
chores, and instead we
prioritize

50:26.790 --> 50:31.729 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
their homework and enrichment
activities over all else.

50:31.729 --> 50:37.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this leads to young adults
who can't do the basic tasks
associated with living life

50:37.067 --> 50:42.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on their own. A fellow college
dean on another campus told me
of a kid whose parents installed

50:42.306 --> 50:48.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a webcam in the dorm room in
order to wake their kid up each
morning in college. A student

50:48.145 --> 50:52.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
told me of a friend whose
parents always filled her car
with gas, so she never learned.

50:52.950 --> 50:57.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then while driving one day
in her 20s, she noticed her tank
was low on fuel, and

50:57.254 --> 51:01.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
she ended up filling the car
with diesel, instead of
unleaded. And some parents are

51:01.659 --> 51:04.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so accustomed to arguing over
grades in high school and
college, that they expect to do

51:04.828 --> 51:07.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the same in the workplace.

51:07.364 --> 51:12.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A manager at a prestigious
company told me of hearing from
parents of an employee who

51:12.102 --> 51:16.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were dissatisfied with their --
quote, unquote -- "child"'s
performance review.

51:16.340 --> 51:21.445 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Do parents do that?
Yes, parents do.

51:21.445 --> 51:27.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Look, we love our kids with a
driving force we can barely
comprehend. I think of it as

51:27.551 --> 51:34.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an aching, fierce, terror joy.
Of course, we want the very best
for them. And we love

51:34.024 --> 51:37.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be needed, and we feel a
great deal of satisfaction when
we ensure that their needs

51:37.795 --> 51:40.698 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
are met.

51:40.698 --> 51:45.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But overhelping can come at a
significant long-term cost to
our kids. It deprives them

51:45.769 --> 51:50.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of the chance to build
self-efficacy, a critical aspect
of psychological wellness that
comes

51:50.607 --> 51:55.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from seeing that one's own
actions lead to outcomes, one's
own actions, not one's parents'

51:55.946 --> 51:59.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
actions on one's behalf.

51:59.550 --> 52:03.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We end up raising kids who fail
to launch, who don't have their
the wherewithal to do

52:03.554 --> 52:08.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for themselves, and who still
need us to act as the adult in
their lives.

52:08.892 --> 52:14.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No matter how impressive our
kid's childhood GPA or resume
may be, we have simply not done

52:14.465 --> 52:20.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right by our kids, our society,
our species, if they have
reached the age of chronological

52:20.170 --> 52:30.514 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
adulthood, but don't have the
skills, habits, mind-sets, and
confidence to do for themselves.

